The paper discusses the construction of codes for DNA-based information storage, which involves the use of finite-state transducers, error correction, synchronization, and encoding into DNA sequences that avoid short local repeats. These topics are relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, including data structures (cs.DS), cryptography and security (cs.CR), information theory (cs.IT), databases (cs.DB), and computational engineering, finance, and science (cs.CE).
